SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) ğŸ’¯ ok, so hereâ€™s what i want to say about these. if youâ€™ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthinâ€™ ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they arenâ€™t then beware of the SOG ğŸ˜!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didnâ€™t know that coffee cake doesnâ€™t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake â€˜coffee cakeâ€™ if it doesnâ€™t contain coffee? ğŸ™„ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ itâ€™s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but itâ€™s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and thatâ€™s really all you need to knowğŸ™Š.
.
cakeâ€”
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
toppingâ€”
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) ğŸ’¯ ok, so hereâ€™s what i want to say about these. if youâ€™ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthinâ€™ ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they arenâ€™t then beware of the SOG ğŸ˜!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didnâ€™t know that coffee cake doesnâ€™t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake â€˜coffee cakeâ€™ if it doesnâ€™t contain coffee? ğŸ™„ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ itâ€™s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but itâ€™s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and thatâ€™s really all you need to knowğŸ™Š.
.
cakeâ€”
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
toppingâ€”
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) ğŸ’¯ ok, so hereâ€™s what i want to say about these. if youâ€™ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthinâ€™ ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they arenâ€™t then beware of the SOG ğŸ˜!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didnâ€™t know that coffee cake doesnâ€™t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake â€˜coffee cakeâ€™ if it doesnâ€™t contain coffee? ğŸ™„ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ itâ€™s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but itâ€™s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and thatâ€™s really all you need to knowğŸ™Š.
.
cakeâ€”
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
toppingâ€”
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.

.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) ğŸ’¯ ok, so hereâ€™s what i want to say about these. if youâ€™ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthinâ€™ ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they arenâ€™t then beware of the SOG ğŸ˜!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

for all of your weekend baking needs, here is my gluten free/grain free BLACKBERRY COFFEE CAKE! and am i the only person that didnâ€™t know that coffee cake doesnâ€™t contain coffee? so why would anyone name a cake â€˜coffee cakeâ€™ if it doesnâ€™t contain coffee? ğŸ™„ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ itâ€™s meant to be enjoyed WITH coffee, but itâ€™s irrelevant anyway because this recipe is yummy and thatâ€™s really all you need to knowğŸ™Š.
.
cakeâ€”
1 cup blackberries
1 cup almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
3 eggs
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp baking soda
pinch sea salt
.
toppingâ€”
3/4 cup chopped walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
3 tb coconut sugar
.
preheat oven to 350. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper (grease inside of pan first so the parchment paper sticks). make the topping first, by combining all ingredients in a medium bowl. mix well and set aside. now make the cake by adding all of the ingredients, except the blackberries, and blend until well incorporated. transfer to a medium bowl, and fold in the blackberries. mix well, and you can go ahead and crush some of the blackberries in the batter. pour half of the batter into the baking dish, followed by half of the topping. then add remaining batter and remaining topping. use a spatula to flatten and make even. bake for 40 minutes.

It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal Iâ€™ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldnâ€™t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I neednâ€™t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant Iâ€™ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughtonâ€™s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. Iâ€™ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparentâ€™s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandmaâ€™s Petaluma plant nursery. Iâ€™m very grateful that @light_thiefâ€™s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all yâ€™all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. ğŸ™ğŸ»

SWEET & SALTY CRUNCHY CHICKPEAS (like kettle corn but chickpeas) ğŸ’¯ ok, so hereâ€™s what i want to say about these. if youâ€™ve tried to make something similar in the past but they turned out soggy, then you need to follow my instructions below to get that CRUNCH factor! i like to snack on these by the handful, but you can also use them to top a salad or really anything that needs a little sumthinâ€™ ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
first things first, grab two cans of garbanzo beans and put them in a strainer and rinse well. then lay them on a towel and pat dry and let air dry for an hour. so go run an errand or go to yoga or walk the dog. but the key is that they are DRY before you start, and if they arenâ€™t then beware of the SOG ğŸ˜!
.
turn oven to 400. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. line up chickpeas in a single layer. roast for 30 minutes, stopping every 10 minutes to rotate them so that they dry out evenly, remove from oven, and transfer to a bowl.
.
for the SWEET & SALTY sauce, whisk together the following in a small bowl:
1 tb melted ghee (or avocado oil or olive oil)
2 tb honey (or maple syrup)
1 tsp sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon
.
coat the chickpeas evenly in the sauce and return to the baking sheet and back into the oven for 7-10 more minutes. they will be crispy and stay crispy! store extras in a glass container in the fridge

slice one peach in half. add 1/2 tsp coconut oil to a cast iron skillet, medium heat. place peaches face down in the skillet for 2 minutes. flip to the other side for another two minutes. transfer to a plate, add some cinnamon, a drizzle of coconut milk and manuka honey, and heyyyyyyyy party in your mouth!

welcome to muffin monday ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and itâ€™s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, iâ€™m just saying ğŸ˜ iâ€™ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so hereâ€™s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. hereâ€™s how to make themğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda

pinch sea salt

Mushroom Paitan Ramen from last week ğŸœğŸ„. I used the Vegan Ramen recipe from my blog as a base and added a Ajitama because I could not resist. I would usually add a roasted vegetables to this dish, but these noodles booked end a yakitori night so I held back.

I am getting hungry just thinking about it.

Congratulations to @ramen.chef and @taishoken.usa for opening up an amazing ramen shop! ğŸŠ I remember it was not too long ago where Yoshi talked about opening up his own shop. All the hard work that he put in really shows in the quality of the shop. This easily makes my Top 3 list of ramen in the US. For a moment, I felt like I was eating ramen back in Japan. ğŸœ

I was very fortunate to get a sneak peak of his ramen this past Friday and try out 3 of their ramen. Their Tokusei Tsukemen, Ramen, and Spicy Ramen.

The meal started with their potato salad with an ajitama and salted mullet roe. Something so simple was so delicious. It was preview of the rest of the meal to come.

The Tokusei Ramen brings a rich broth of pork and chicken that coats your mouth. The flavors were very balanced with from the first to the last sip. It came with medium-thin noodles that had a very smooth slurp and a pleasant chew.
My biggest complaint with spicy ramen is that the spice is very one dimensional. The Spicy Tokusei Ramen was very complex - smokey, floral, with a little bit of heat. I scratch my head trying to pick out all of the flavors. Just like the regular ramen this bowl was balanced.

My favorite bowl of the night is the Tokusei Tsukemen. The gyokai dipping broth was a nice balance of pork, chicken, and fish flavors. The real star of this dish were the noodles. Thick, chewy, and buckwheat forward flavors. The noodles are made in house and it really shows.

The best bowls of ramen to me are ones that are always balanced. At Taishoken, I had 3 bowls that were completely different and they were each made with the same amount of thoughtfulness, with every component meaningful to the bowl.

The grand opening is this Wednesday, July 17th, so get your bowl before the word spreads and the 1-2 hour waits begin!

My homemade ramen noodles after a week of resting. They have developed a slurpier and smoother texture.

Even though these noodles are at 36% hydration, they have a slight hard bite to them similar to hakata style noodles. It might be that whole wheat flour needs more water that just bread flour by itself.

I am ready to move on to my next batch so I can learn more. ğŸ‘¨ğŸ»â€ğŸ”¬ Definitely going to make less than 10 servings though. I don't eat as many noodles as I used to.

-
1 large sweet potato (with the orange flesh!)
2 tb avocado oil
1/2 tsp sea salt
seasonings of choice (sprinkle on anything you like, i donâ€™t obsess over measurements, just sprinkle and have funâ€”garlic powder, oregano, cumin, etc. i used @primalpalate seafood seasoning bc itâ€™s lemony and yum!)

dipping sauceâ€”

hereâ€™s how to make it:

i never really considered myself a MORNING GLORY MUFFIN kind of gal, but wouldnâ€™t you know, here i am ğŸ‘µğŸ¼ i made a version of my girl @lauraleabalancedâ€™s jumbo morning glory muffins, and yeah...pretty convinced that youâ€™re going to be obsessed too ğŸ’¯ you can find the original (banana-less) recipe on lauraâ€™s blog, and my version is here for you below! you can see what they look like inside on my IG stories. -
ingredients:
1 cup rolled oats
1 cup gluten free flour (or whole wheat or spelt)
1 banana
2 eggs
2 tsp baking soda
1 apple (i like pink lady)
2 medium carrots
1/2 cup raisins
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 tsp nutmeg
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup coconut sugar
2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup walnuts, chopped
pinch sea salt
-
instructions:
preheat oven to 350 and line a muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, mix together 1/2 cup of the oats, baking soda, flour, sea salt, coconut sugar, cinnamon, and nutmeg. set aside. in a food processor or blender, add remaining oats and pulse/blend until a flour consistency is formed, set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the eggs, vanilla, and coconut milk. next, core the apple, peel carrots, and add them to the blender, along with the banana. pulse/blend lightly until a crumble like consistency is formed. pour wet ingredients into dry, and fold in the raisins and walnuts, be sure not to overmix! spoon batter into each muffin cavity. i made regular size muffins and 28 min in the oven was perfect!

hereâ€™s what you need for the muffins:

hereâ€™s how to make them:

Mushroom #Vegan ramen is the noodle dish you didn't know you wanted. Lucky for you it is quick to make and a great substitute for tonkotsu ramen lovers. Check out the recipe link in my bio. This is the same recipe that I served at my Portland Popup with @kukiesslurpshack!

This weekend was one of the rare times that I make ramen for my parents. I do see my parents once a week, but I have been very fortunate and spoiled to have a home cook meal prepared for me when I visit.

When I do cook for my parents, I want to make it special, yet simple and healthy. I started with a very simple chicken stock made from @maryschicken. The stock was so clean and refreshing it was worth spending a few extra bucks. The golden broth was combined with a Mushroom Shoyu Tare leftover from my last popup. I topped the bowl with some asparagus sauteed in garlic, some kurobuta tenderloin, and of course a marinade egg.

My parents are people of few words when it comes to describing tasty food, but will speak volumes when they eat something they don't like. I didn't hear any complaints and my mom saved her leftover broth for later, so I will take that as a win.

Cooking at my parents house always reminds me of the beginning of my ramen journey. It is always good to reflect on the past every once and a while and evaluate my progress before looking towards the future and seeing what is next.

Tantanmen testing for my next pop-up on May 11th ğŸ‘¨ğŸ»â€ğŸ”¬ğŸŒ¶ï¸. Stay tuned for more details.

I started with the mushroom/cashew base that I used for my latest Vegan Ramen and amped it up with some sesame paste, peanut butter, garlic, and soy sauce. It is always amazing to see how a few ingredients can transform it into something completely different. It is topped with a little bit of szechuan peppercorns and ichimi to give it a little kick. My chili oil is a work in progress, but the habanero peppers I added pushed it in the right direction.

i woke up thinking oh itâ€™s toast tuesday, i should make toast, but instead i was craving a big ass smoothie and didnâ€™t feel like taking pictures, so iâ€™m sharing one of my all time favorite recipes with you, my PALEO CRUNCHY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES! so good, guaranteed to bring all the boys to the yard ğŸ˜‚ğŸ™„ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¸ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ kidding, sorta. hereâ€™s the recipe:
.
1 cup almond butter
3/4 cup coconut sugar
1 egg
1 tsp baking soda
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together all the ingredients except the chocolate chips. then fold in 1/2 of the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop to form 10 cookies. make sure to spread them out because the dough spreads in the oven. sprinkle remaining chocolate chips on top. bake 12-13 minutes. remove from oven and let cool. they will flatten out some more and get a little more crunchy! #kalejunkie

Fishbone crouton. This is an extension to our caesar salad dish featuring Bay Area sardines; meant to be eaten as a snack. The sardine bones are salted, rinsed and dried, smoked, and then lightly fried. Before serving they are seasoned with a mixture of bread ingredients. This mixture includes grains that are fermented, sprouted, grilled, and dried. We ground the mixture to a powder and add yeast. The result is a crunchy crouton with flavors of smoky dried bread. Tasty use of the entire fish. ğŸ“¸ @croissantsandcaviar and @engagingaesthetics

BACK TO BASICS ğŸŒ when you want a banana bread that contains no added sugar (sweetened only from banana), but still tastes like it came from a bakery, you make this anything but basic CINNAMON BANANA BREAD ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ itâ€™s different than your usual banana bread in that itâ€™s lighter â€” itâ€™s not a dense brick that will sit in your stomach all day, but rather a soft and chewy pillow with a slightly crunchy top ğŸ˜‰ did i convince you yet? iâ€™ve included the recipe for you below, and iâ€™ll get it up on the blog later today so you can find it anytime! happy tuesday! â¤ï¸ #kalejunkie
-
1 1/2 cups almond flour
1/4 cup tapioca flour
3 tb coconut flour
4 super ripe bananas (if they are large, use 3)
3 eggs
1 tsp vanilla extract
2 tb cinnamon
1 tsp baking soda
1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp sea salt
note: ** you can add any toppings you want, chocolate chips, nuts, etc.
-
preheat oven to 350. line a loaf pan with parchment paper (spray inside with oil first so paper sticks). in a medium bowl, whisk together dry ingredients. in a blender, blend the bananas and wet ingredients for about 10-15 seconds until just incorporated (some chunks are ok!). pour wet ingredients into the bowl with the dry ingredients and mix lightly until combined. pour into the loaf pan and smooth out the top with a spatula. bake for 40-45 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. let cool, sprinkle a little more cinnamon on top and enjoyyyyyyy ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼

iâ€™ve got some new PALEO FUDGY BROWNIES for you guys. they are super fudgy and chewy, filled with chocolate chips, and yet still light! so if you are looking for something to bake today, iâ€™ve got you!
.
hereâ€™s how to make them:
3 eggs
1/2 cup coconut sugar
1/2 cup almond flour
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb cacao powder
1/4 cup coffee, cooled
3/4 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
pinch sea salt
.
preheat oven to 325. line an 8x8 baking dish with parchment paper and set aside (oil the baking dish so paper sticks). in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs and coconut sugar for about two minutes, until well combined and there are no clumps. stir in the almond flour, coconut flour, cacao, coffee, coconut oil, and sea salt. mix until combined. fold in the chocolate chips. pour batter into the baking dish. bake for 35-37 minutes, or until a toothpick comes out clean! remove from oven and slice into 12 squares. enjoyyyyyyyy! #kalejunkie

happy saturday everyone! iâ€™m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didnâ€™t share the recipeâ€”i feel like iâ€™m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things ğŸ™ŠğŸ™ˆ! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share ğŸ˜‰ off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies â€” add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms ğŸ› and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if youâ€™d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

morning ğŸ‘‹ğŸ¼ today iâ€™m sharing ZUCCHINI CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES, of the vegan kind. i had a few super ripe bananas around yesterday and one lonely zucchini, so i made these cookies and added @hukitchen df paleo chocolate GEMS because they are crack! hereâ€™s how i made them:
.
2 large spotty bananas
3/4 cup shredded zucchini
1 cup gluten free rolled oats
3/4 cup almond flour
1/2 cup walnuts (optional)
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted and cooled
1/4 cup maple syrup
1 tsp cinnamon
1 tsp salt
1 tsp baking soda
3/4 cup dairy free chocolate (code KALEJUNKIE saves you 10% off all @hukitchen orders!)
.
preheat oven to 350. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. shred your zucchiniâ€”you must take paper towels and soak up as much moisture as you can! in a medium bowl, mash the bananas well. then add shredded zucchini, and the other wet ingredients. in another bowl, mix together the dry ingredients and then pour into the bowl with the wet. fold in the chocolate chips. use a cookie scoop and form 12 cookies. bake for 12-14 minutes. they should still look a little soft when removed from the oven, thatâ€™s okay! they settle nicely. store in the fridge for up to one week! #kalejunkie

caption_text: First bowl of Ramen on my NYC trip. Met up with @the_original_kano and @ramenover for some fancy smancy tonkotsu at @tonchinnewyork . Do you know what? This bowl was awesome. I have gotten tired of tonkotsu lately and this bowl has made me a fan once again. It wasn't too heavy and more complex then just porky gelatanous soup. The egg and chashu were amazing and they make their own noodles too. Just the right amount of bite. I love how they designed everything to match, from the napkins and bowls down the the walls. It was an $18 bowl of ramen but it was delicious none the less. ğŸ·ğŸœ

Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. ğŸ„ğŸœ It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

Shoyu Ramen testing ğŸœğŸ§ª I cracked open a few bottles of soy sauce that I had in my pantry for a while. The one that got my attention is a double brewed (saishikomi) soy sauce. This is where the produces uses already brewed soy sauce in the place of water and salt in the normal brewing process. It is not overly salty, but has an intense umami flavor that almost tasted fishy to me.

I am hoping to make a simple recipe that anyone can make at home. This recipe is so far so good! I want to tweak it a bit before posting. The made the bowl with some homemade noodles and I am pretty satisfied with how it turned out!

Who else likes shoyu ramen? I haven't really been a big fan, but I am getting more and more into it!
Yes, we have Topo Chico! For all you sparkling water heads. (And fried chicken for the rest of us)
I like that @tildenhotel guests have access to free coffee and water and a discount to all food and beverage orders. Jameel from the Tilden Cafe created the best hot mocha I have ever tasted! â¤ï¸

when that shadow hits justtttt right ğŸ˜ğŸ˜ğŸ˜ i made these GARLIC & ROSEMARY SWEET POTATO FRIES to go with my dinner last night and i wanted to share with you guys because they came out SO GOOD!
-
all you have to do is turn your oven to 400. chop two medium size japanese sweet potatoes into 1/2 inch thick pieces (like fries). toss them in a bowl, and coat with 3 tb avocado oil, 2 tb arrowroot flour, 1/2 tsp salt, 1 tb garlic powder, 1 tb dried rosemary. line them up in a single layer on a parchment lined baking sheet. bake for 20-22 minutes, flipping at the half way point. sprinkle with sea salt flakes!

Finally made it to Mayflower restaurant (Hong Kong flower lounge) for dim sum - itâ€™s very close to SFO. The service is very friendly (honestly i donâ€™t care if service is bad as long as the dim sum is good but this is a plus). Their zha liang (steamed rice rolls that are usually filled with Chinese donut/you tiao) is filled instead with deep fried bean curd skin wrapped shrimp. Quality is top notch but i personally prefer the original zha liang. Still, a very satisfying meal. We had Siu mai, shrimp dumplings, spareribs, chicken feet and this egg plant thing filled with shrimp paste. All were delicious.

Happy (toast) Tuesday! This toasted egg sandwich with smashed avocado is 100%! I mixed 1 hard boiled, pasture-raised egg with 1 tbsp avocado mayonnaise and 1 tsp dijon mustard, and spread it on top of some micro greens on 1 slice of toasted sprouted grain bread, then added some smashed avocado seasoned with salt, pepper and a squeeze of lemon, and finished with some sauteed organic spinach and the other piece of toasted bread. I usually use untoasted bread for my sandwiches but once in a while it's good to switch things up, and the toasting of the bread gives it additional texture. Speaking of texture, I paired this sandwich with a side of @fitjoy crunchy, addictive nacho cheese puffs - these are conveniently portioned, and contain 3-4 net carbs and 17-18G protein per bag, and are #grainless and #glutenfree. The nacho cheese flavor is very tasty and I love the crunchy texture! More dEATS and a discount code in my IG stories ğŸ§€ğŸ˜‹ #fitjoypartner

Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. ğŸ„ğŸœ It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

Mushroom Paitan Ramen from last week ğŸœğŸ„. I used the Vegan Ramen recipe from my blog as a base and added a Ajitama because I could not resist. I would usually add a roasted vegetables to this dish, but these noodles booked end a yakitori night so I held back.

I am getting hungry just thinking about it.
[013] Tonkotsu Ramen ğŸœğŸ· - I hardly make Tonkotsu, but I have to admit this was really good. Added some gyofun which really completed the bowl. Time to turn this into tsukemen next.

My homemade ramen noodles after a week of resting. They have developed a slurpier and smoother texture.

Even though these noodles are at 36% hydration, they have a slight hard bite to them similar to hakata style noodles. It might be that whole wheat flour needs more water that just bread flour by itself.

I am ready to move on to my next batch so I can learn more. ğŸ‘¨ğŸ»â€ğŸ”¬ Definitely going to make less than 10 servings though. I don't eat as many noodles as I used to.

Shoyu Ramen testing ğŸœğŸ§ª I cracked open a few bottles of soy sauce that I had in my pantry for a while. The one that got my attention is a double brewed (saishikomi) soy sauce. This is where the produces uses already brewed soy sauce in the place of water and salt in the normal brewing process. It is not overly salty, but has an intense umami flavor that almost tasted fishy to me.

I am hoping to make a simple recipe that anyone can make at home. This recipe is so far so good! I want to tweak it a bit before posting. The made the bowl with some homemade noodles and I am pretty satisfied with how it turned out!

Who else likes shoyu ramen? I haven't really been a big fan, but I am getting more and more into it!

Thinking about the #noodles I had at @afuripdx. I learned that Afuri decided to have it's first US location in Portland because their soft and pure water similar to what is going in Japan. Perfect for making noodles. I still have a lot of things to learn about noodle making! ğŸœ #liftingnoodles

This weekend was one of the rare times that I make ramen for my parents. I do see my parents once a week, but I have been very fortunate and spoiled to have a home cook meal prepared for me when I visit.

When I do cook for my parents, I want to make it special, yet simple and healthy. I started with a very simple chicken stock made from @maryschicken. The stock was so clean and refreshing it was worth spending a few extra bucks. The golden broth was combined with a Mushroom Shoyu Tare leftover from my last popup. I topped the bowl with some asparagus sauteed in garlic, some kurobuta tenderloin, and of course a marinade egg.

My parents are people of few words when it comes to describing tasty food, but will speak volumes when they eat something they don't like. I didn't hear any complaints and my mom saved her leftover broth for later, so I will take that as a win.

Cooking at my parents house always reminds me of the beginning of my ramen journey. It is always good to reflect on the past every once and a while and evaluate my progress before looking towards the future and seeing what is next.

i made some PALEO TAHINI FOCACCIA with fresh herbs and sea salt using @simplemills artisan bread mix and i feel like a tahini ninja, what ever that is ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ anyway, greg is having a minor surgery today so iâ€™ll be spending the rest of the day taking care of him, so iâ€™m leaving you with these baddies and signing offâ€”you can pick up the @simplemills bread mix over at @wholefoods (i found it in the baking aisle!). itâ€™s so easy and you wonâ€™t believe how tasty!
.
one package @simplemills artisan bread mix
2 tb olive oil
3 tb tahini
1 tb water
2 tb apple cider vinegar
2 organic pasture raised eggs
toppings: chopped herbs of choice (i used chives and microgreens) and sea salt
.
in a medium bowl, whisk together the wet ingredients. slowly add the bread mix, and stir until combined. let sit for four minutes. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. form a ball with the dough. wet hands so dough doesnâ€™t stick to your hands and place it on the parchment paper, and flatten evenly into a rectangle shape, about 1/2 inch thick. bake for 15 minutes. remove from oven and top with herbs and sea salt. boom there it is ğŸ’¥ #kalejunkie #simplemillspartner

happy easter, friends!! ğŸ£ğŸ° there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! ğŸ‘‹ğŸ¼), iâ€™ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, hereâ€™s my Faux Reeseâ€™s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because thereâ€™s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! ğŸ˜‰

hereâ€™s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

hereâ€™s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

to make the cherry jam, you just need one cup of frozen cherries and 1/4 cup chia seeds (you can use fresh cherries, but you need to remove the pits). place the cherries and chia seeds in a small pot over low/medium heat, stirring constantly and mashing the cherries. after about 5-7 minutes, remove from heat and let sit for about 5 minutes, so that the chia gels and the jam thickens! store any extra in the fridge for up to one weekâœ¨ happy friday everyone!!! #kalejunkie

It has been two years since we've lost Gus and we still miss his presence greatly.
Despite that, we know that his vision and hands are on everything we do as a market. Gus had a heart for building long-term relationships with vendors, producers, and farmers throughout California, many of which we still do business with today. He loved San Francisco and always made sure to give back to local communities and causes that built up our neighborhoods. He put family first, including all employees, and always saw success as running a business that supports other families. Not a day goes by we don't run it like Gus is in it!
Thank you for everything--we love you, we love you! ğŸ’š

caption_text:
happy easter, friends!! ğŸ£ğŸ° there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! ğŸ‘‹ğŸ¼), iâ€™ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, hereâ€™s my Faux Reeseâ€™s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because thereâ€™s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! ğŸ˜‰

hereâ€™s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

hereâ€™s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)
.
4 strawberries, chopped into small pieces
1 egg
1 tb maple syrup
1/2 tsp baking powder
3 tb almond flour
1 tb coconut flour
2 tb dairy free chocolate chips
.
in a large mug, whisk together the egg and maple syrup. then add the rest of the ingredients and mix well, reserving a few strawberries and chocolate chips to sprinkle on top. microwave for 2-3 minutes. ENJOY!!!! #kalejunkie

Zha jiang mian - black bean sauce noodles. Step by step recipe is up on IG stories and in IG highlights! Many of you have asked if I have a blog. This is my blog, and Iâ€™ll continue to add step by step recipes to my highlights - feel free to browse up there and see what tickles your fancy. But as many of you already know and resonate, Asian cooking does not measure things down to the gram. I grew up watching my grandma and my mum throwing a spoonful of this, a splash of that, etc. as they go along, and thatâ€™s exactly what I do. Sometimes I offer rough measurements for those of you that want to see that, but I strongly encourage you to do the former (when you make Chinese food, not when you bake that angel food cake): taste as you go along. Certain things you can add more liberally (soy sauce, cooking wine) and others you start with little amounts (salt, sugar, sesame oil, fish sauce, vinegar... things that are stronger in taste) and adjust as you go along. Also a useful tip: if you feel that youâ€™ve added too much salt, soy sauce, fish sauce or vinegar, one way to partially salvage a dish is to add more sugar. I use white or raw or brown sugar and it usually doesnâ€™t matter which one I use in my recipes. But never artificial sweeteners. We eat a lot and we are fairly healthy and in shape. Everything in moderation and certainly no dieting over here ğŸ™ŒğŸ»ğŸ™ŒğŸ» .

From Castro to Greenwich, U Dessert Story opened their second cafe, U Dessert Story: Vintage. Unlike their casual dessert focused cafe, Vintage brings Asian fusion dishes in the house including Japanese Omurice and Ube Smoked Salmon Toast. Don't forget to finish off with their house made desserts. Run your fork through a thousand layers matcha goodness presented on a vintage golden plate.

In my happy place. It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal Iâ€™ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldnâ€™t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I neednâ€™t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant Iâ€™ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughtonâ€™s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. Iâ€™ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparentâ€™s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandmaâ€™s Petaluma plant nursery. Iâ€™m very grateful that @light_thiefâ€™s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all yâ€™all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. ğŸ™ğŸ»

ARIA is this little gem ğŸ’ of a restaurant located in San Francisco. ğŸŒ‰ One of our favorite places to go to in the city. ğŸŒƒ The whole restaurant is covered with these really cool stickers and graffiti! ğŸŒ† It has that modern street art pop style to it. Homemade Taiwanese Beef Noodle Soup by my wife using @thewoksoflife recipe. ğŸ„ğŸœ It has been too hot the past few weeks to make ramen. So the day we made beef noodle soup, our place got up to 90 degrees inside so we finally budged and turned on the AC. Fall cannot come soon enough, but for now I will have to sweat it out while my broth turns my place into a sauna.
Of course I had to use ramen noodles in my bowl. The temomi noodles from @sunnoodles was pretty good, but the noodles for beef noodle soup needs to have a higher hydration for a chewier bite. We used udon for our second time which paired very well.

STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)
.
4 strawberries, chopped into small pieces
1 egg
1 tb maple syrup
1/2 tsp baking powder
3 tb almond flour
1 tb coconut flour
2 tb dairy free chocolate chips
.
in a large mug, whisk together the egg and maple syrup. then add the rest of the ingredients and mix well, reserving a few strawberries and chocolate chips to sprinkle on top. microwave for 2-3 minutes. ENJOY!!!! #kalejunkie

welcome to muffin monday ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and itâ€™s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, iâ€™m just saying ğŸ˜ iâ€™ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so hereâ€™s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. hereâ€™s how to make themğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
pinch sea salt
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1/4 cup @obourfoods tahini
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
3/4 cup @hukitchen chocolate gems
.
preheat oven to 375. line muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together all of the dry ingredients and set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the coconut oil, tahini, eggs, and vanilla. pour bowl with dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. fold in the chocolate pieces. use a spoon to fill the muffin cavities, making 5 large muffins or 8 regular size. bake for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. enjoy!!!!!!!!!! #kalejunkie

sunday calls for my PROCIUTTO, ARUGULA & LEMON PIZZA, made with a cauliflower pizza crust! itâ€™s super easy to make, super flavorful, and yesâ€”you can eat the lemon! if you want to try it in person, meet me tomorrow at the @specialtyfoodassociationâ€™s winter fancy food showâ€”iâ€™ll be at the @caulipowered booth (#6719) from 11:30am-12pm, and they will be making them on-site. otherwise, go grab one of these pizza crusts and try the recipe!
.
1 @caulipowered plain crust pizza
1/2 cup pizza sauce
1/4 cup shredded sheep milk pecorino cheese
2 oz prosciutto
1 meyer lemon, thinly sliced
small handful arugula
everything but the bagel seasoning
.
preheat oven to 425 and place pizza crust on a baking sheet. spread a thin layer of pizza sauce evenly, followed by the cheese and the lemon slices. bake for 13 minutes. remove from oven, top with prosciutto, arugula and everything but the bagel seasoning. slice and enjoy! #caulipowered #ad

Making Nalysnyky aka French crepes is the recipe that runs in our family through generations. The tradition started with my grandma and continues with me. Nalysnyky was the first dish I ever made for my friends when I moved to Kyiv and started my adult life. I still have the warmest feelings for these thin, buttery blini, which are mind-blowingly good when served hot straight from the frying pan. I always make them for my husband when he asks for something special for breakfast, and serve with homemade jam or quick fruit compote. If you're ready to master this dish, I have a perfect recipe for you: https://vivalafood.com/basic-crepes-recipe/

In my happy place. It was such an overwhelming pleasure to be able to experience the early, mid and late summer menus at @singlethreadfarms this season and get to see the development of dishes as peak seasonality of products changed. Every meal Iâ€™ve had at ST has been flawless perfection, which can pose a problem for a restaurant in how do they top the last experience?when I decided to do this, I was nervous maybe there wouldnâ€™t be enough variation in the menus month to month for me to keep the upward trajectory of smitten-ness going full steam but I neednâ€™t have worried. Somehow I always leave even more blown away than my previous trip to ST which is so beautiful. The synchronicity between all the teams is unreal. Service is warm, welcoming and comfortable while being simultaneously the most polished of any restaurant Iâ€™ve ever dined in. I really love how the customized reserve pairings have evolved as Alex and Alex have gained more knowledge of my personal tastes (though it was always fucking mind blowing). @kyleconnaughtonâ€™s food is always B-A-N-A-N-A-S amazing, and there is enough turnover in the menu to support multiple trips in a single season. Iâ€™ll post up all the food pics in a few days time and sorry to be repetitive but as I rambled on about the last time, the food is emotional, both incredibly exciting and new while also concurrently deeply nostalgic and familiar for a northern CA kid who grew up eating so many of these same produce varietals @lumberjackieo grows at the farm from my grandparentâ€™s ranch not 20 miles away and saw so many of the same flowers grown at my grandmaâ€™s Petaluma plant nursery. Iâ€™m very grateful that @light_thiefâ€™s birthday, my birthday and now our wedding anniversary all fall a month-ish apart each so I have the perfect excuse to do this shit every year now as long as I can continue to finance this addiction. Thank you to all yâ€™all on the ST team who always make us feel like family when we are there and continue to make every meal newly the best of my life each time, over and over. Also, deeply, deeply appreciate you guys sharing some of that really special bottle with us. ğŸ™ğŸ»

[023] Karashibi Tori Paitan Ramen ğŸŒ¶ï¸ğŸ”ğŸœ - I made a second iteration of my spice oil to mix with my thick and creamy chicken broth. *RAMEN FACT* In the word Karashibi, "Kara" is the typical burning heat from something like a dried red pepper or korean pepper flakes. "Shibi" is the numbing spice you get from a Szechuan peppercorn. So in Karashibi ramen, you the best of both worlds. A spice that affects both the taste and touch/feeling of your mouth.

The numbing spicd can mask the heat and flavor in a bowl or ramen, so it is good to bump of the flavors more than usual to make sure it doesn't taste "bland".

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS ğŸ‹ eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? ğŸ˜‰) note, i havenâ€™t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, iâ€™d suggest just making them as is! ğŸ‹
-
hereâ€™s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
hereâ€™s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but itâ€™s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutesâ€”the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, youâ€™ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

Extra-spiced pumpkin spice Mexican hot chocolate muffins with sea salt! Getting on a flight later and most plane food grosses me out, so Iâ€™m packing these homemade muffins to bring with me, along with this beautiful box of calavera burnt caramel truffles I received from @recchiuticonfections. What snacks do you like to bring with you on a long flight?â£
â£â£
I have a trusted pumpkin spice muffin recipe Iâ€™ve been making for years but when I received these DÃ­a de Muertos themed truffles, they inspired me to take the â€œspiceâ€ in â€œpumpkin spiceâ€ to the next level. I incorporated shards of spicy chocolate, flavored with cayenne pepper and cinnamon like the delicious hot chocolate I had in Mexico. To make them, I melted 1 cup of bittersweet chocolate chips in a double boiler and combined with 1 tsp cayenne pepper powder and generous dashes of cinnamon. Then I spread the chocolate on a lined baking sheet and stuck it in the freezer until it fully set, and cut it up into irregular pieces.â£
â£
I dislike Halloween celebrations but love macabre things, so I prefer to participate with DÃ­a de Muertos. (And they are not the same thing.) Sugar skulls, or calaveras, are decorated and placed on ofrendas to honor dead loved ones but I also learned that the celebration includes gifting more palatable chocolate skulls as a reminder of our mortality, and to therefore savor the sweetness of life. These melt-in-your-mouth truffles from @recchiuticonfections with their beautiful calavera design are totally perfect for this purpose. #Recchuitiâ£
â£
Be sure to look out for my stories to see what adventures I get up to after I arrive at my next destination!â£

I tried Kuro Obi the other week - a fast food concept by Ippudo at the San Mateo Hillsdale mall. I am skeptical of fast food/mall ramen, but I figured it can't be too bad if it's by Ippudo... but curiosity killed the cat. ğŸ˜¿

The concept is pretty solid, however the execution wasn't there. The first thing I noticed was the tare. The server just had to put one full ladle into eat bowl, but it was haphazardly thrown in and maybe. 1/4 of it was spilled in the side. Since the tare has all of the salt an seasoning, you have to make sure that all of it makes it into the bowl. Second the person manning the noodle station did not have a timer. Some ramen chefs have a good sense of when the noodles are done and other noodles have a large window for when they need to be taken out. I do not think that this was the case.

So how was it? Both bowls fell flat. It was under seasoned and the noodles we're a little undercooked (my biggest pet peeve). The person in charge likely makes a test bowl ahead of time, and if everything is measured out and timed properly, I am sure it tastes just right. The staff that is actually making the bowl might not know what they are doing wrong, which is a little unfortunate since these bowls can be greatly improved with a little more TLC.

happy easter, friends!! ğŸ£ğŸ° there are so many new peeps around here (hi!! ğŸ‘‹ğŸ¼), iâ€™ll do a proper intro soon so that i can get to know YOU guys too!! in the meantime, hereâ€™s my Faux Reeseâ€™s Peanut Butter Cup recipe, because thereâ€™s still time to make them and impress your friends and fam today! ğŸ˜‰

hereâ€™s what you need:
1 cup creamy peanut butter
2 tb coconut flour
3 tb maple syrup
1 cup dairy free chocolate chips
1 tsp coconut oil
1/4 cup cacao nibs (optional, but adds crunch)

hereâ€™s how to make them:
line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a large bowl, whisk together peanut butter, coconut flour, and maple syrup. dough should be thick. form 12-14 balls and place them on the parchment paper. then form each one into an egg shape. place in freezer for 20 minutes. make then chocolate dipping sauce by melting the chocolate and coconut oil in a bowl in the microwave in 30 second increments, until smooth and liquidy. fold in cacao nibs. remove eggs from the freezer and dip each one in the chocolate and place back in the sheet. repeat until all are covered in chocolate. place into the fridge for 20-30 minutes to harden. #kalejunkie

did you know you can also BAKE Trader Joeâ€™s cauliflower gnocchi and make a quick, one pan meal? they will still turn out nice and crunchy, and you can have dinner on your table in minutes! this is an ITALIAN INSPIRED ONE PAN CAULIFLOWER GNOCCHI and iâ€™m super excited to tell you how i made it because youâ€™ll be surprised how flavorful this meal is and how tasty healthy can be! again, ignore the preparation instructions on the gnocchi package and follow mine below!):
-
hereâ€™s what you need:
one package @traderjoes cauliflower gnocchi, frozen!
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1-2 sweet bell peppers, roughly chopped
1 small red onion, thinly sliced
pinch chopped basil
2 tb avocado oil (or oil of choice)
2 tb italian seasoning
pinch of salt / pepper
parmesan cheese to top (optional)
-
hereâ€™s how to make it:
preheat oven to 425 degrees. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and use your hands to ensure everything is coated well with the oil (if you use too much oil, the gnocchi will not be crunchy). pour contents from the bowl onto the baking sheet. bake for 20 minutes. remove from oven and use tongs to toss everything. bake for another 10 minutes. remove from oven and top with the parmesan cheese if youâ€™d like! enjoy ğŸ˜‰ #kalejunkie

Summer melon, a dish that we will be saying goodbye to very soon as melon season comes to an end. A refreshing combination of cantaloupe, honeydew, piel de sapo, geisha, and canary melons to end our current fruit sequence. These various fresh melons are compressed in a syrup made from aromatic herbs such as mint, parsley, oxalis, and citrus marigold. Next, we make a melon sorbet and add a dry sake to balance the sweetness of the melon. The dish is finished with a chamomile gelee and garnished with citrus marigold.

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS ğŸ‹ eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? ğŸ˜‰) note, i havenâ€™t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, iâ€™d suggest just making them as is! ğŸ‹
-
hereâ€™s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
hereâ€™s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but itâ€™s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutesâ€”the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, youâ€™ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

welcome to muffin monday ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ or should i say CHOCOLATE CHUNK TAHINI MUFFINS and itâ€™s probably a good idea that you call in sick from work today to stay home and make them, iâ€™m just saying ğŸ˜ iâ€™ve been getting a lot of requests for banana-free recipes, so hereâ€™s one for you guys. these muffs are also paleo friendly, dairy free, gluten free, grain free, and taste like they came straight from a bakery! the recipe makes 5 large muffins or 8 regular size muffins. hereâ€™s how to make themğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼
.
1/3 cup coconut flour
1/3 cup almond flour
1/4 cup coconut sugar
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
pinch sea salt
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1/4 cup @obourfoods tahini
2 eggs
1 tsp vanilla
3/4 cup @hukitchen chocolate gems
.
preheat oven to 375. line muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together all of the dry ingredients and set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the coconut oil, tahini, eggs, and vanilla. pour bowl with dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. fold in the chocolate pieces. use a spoon to fill the muffin cavities, making 5 large muffins or 8 regular size. bake for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. enjoy!!!!!!!!!! #kalejunkie

if you are in a dinner rut and need something easy (basically me all the timeğŸ™‹ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸) then my new TOMATO & SPINACH PASTA WITH PISTACHIO â€œPARMESANâ€ recipe is for you. itâ€™s gluten free, dairy free, and vegan, and you can easily customize to make it your own. not vegan? add some chopped sausage and ahhh i bet that would be so good too ğŸ˜‹ iâ€™m off to therapy and then home to test my cinnamon rolls recipe before sharing it this week (SO EXCITED!). anywhoooo, hereâ€™s what you need to make this dish:
.
for the pasta:
2 cups cherry tomatoes
1 cup diced onions
1 large shallot, chopped
4 cloves garlic, mashed
1/4 cup olive oil
1 handful spinach, chopped
1 tsp salt
2 tablespoons italian seasoning
1 tsp honey
1 package pasta of choice (i used gluten free fusilli)
.
for the pistachio parmesan:
1/2 cup pistachios (unsalted)
1 cup nutritional yeast
1/2 tsp sea salt
.
prepare pasta according to package instructions and set aside. in a medium pan, add the olive oil and turn on low/medium heat. add onions, garlic, and shallots. stir for about a few minutes, keeping an eye to make sure it doesnâ€™t burn. while thatâ€™s cooking, place the tomatoes in a medium bowl. use your hands and crush the cherries (just squeeze them!). pour cherries into the sauce pan, along with chopped spinach, honey, italian seasoning, and salt. bring to a simmer and cover for 30 minutes. to make pistachio parmesan, add ingredients to a food processor and pulse till you reach desired consistency. toss pasta with sauce and top with pistachio parmesan. inspired by @adishonhealthy #kalejunkie

happy saturday everyone! iâ€™m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didnâ€™t share the recipeâ€”i feel like iâ€™m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things ğŸ™ŠğŸ™ˆ! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share ğŸ˜‰ off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies â€” add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms ğŸ› and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if youâ€™d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

Zha jiang mian - black bean sauce noodles. Step by step recipe is up on IG stories and in IG highlights! Many of you have asked if I have a blog. This is my blog, and Iâ€™ll continue to add step by step recipes to my highlights - feel free to browse up there and see what tickles your fancy. But as many of you already know and resonate, Asian cooking does not measure things down to the gram. I grew up watching my grandma and my mum throwing a spoonful of this, a splash of that, etc. as they go along, and thatâ€™s exactly what I do. Sometimes I offer rough measurements for those of you that want to see that, but I strongly encourage you to do the former (when you make Chinese food, not when you bake that angel food cake): taste as you go along. Certain things you can add more liberally (soy sauce, cooking wine) and others you start with little amounts (salt, sugar, sesame oil, fish sauce, vinegar... things that are stronger in taste) and adjust as you go along. Also a useful tip: if you feel that youâ€™ve added too much salt, soy sauce, fish sauce or vinegar, one way to partially salvage a dish is to add more sugar. I use white or raw or brown sugar and it usually doesnâ€™t matter which one I use in my recipes. But never artificial sweeteners. We eat a lot and we are fairly healthy and in shape. Everything in moderation and certainly no dieting over here ğŸ™ŒğŸ»ğŸ™ŒğŸ» .

[022] Yuzu Shio Ramen - I made my version of Afuri's famous Yuzu Shio Ramen. My shio ramen isn't quite as delicate but it packs a flavorful punch that competes with the yuzu flavor. [023] Karashibi Tori Paitan Ramen ğŸŒ¶ï¸ğŸ”ğŸœ - I made a second iteration of my spice oil to mix with my thick and creamy chicken broth. *RAMEN FACT* In the word Karashibi, "Kara" is the typical burning heat from something like a dried red pepper or korean pepper flakes. "Shibi" is the numbing spice you get from a Szechuan peppercorn. So in Karashibi ramen, you the best of both worlds. A spice that affects both the taste and touch/feeling of your mouth.

The numbing spicd can mask the heat and flavor in a bowl or ramen, so it is good to bump of the flavors more than usual to make sure it doesn't taste "bland".

What is great is that the fish cake has zero flour and is all meat unlike the stuff you find in restaurants or supermarkets. They are an awesome duo that makes sure my fridge or freezer is always stocked. Lucky me!

Fishcake goes well with any kind of noodle soup especially tonkotsu gyokai. The soup has the richness from the pork bones and a smokey fish flavor from the seafood components. A match made in heaven. ğŸ–ğŸŸğŸœ

happy saturday everyone! iâ€™m finally rolling out my PALEO COPYCAT SAMOA RECIPE in case you want to do something fun in the kitchen this weekend! i forgot i teased it here on my page a few weeks ago and then didnâ€™t share the recipeâ€”i feel like iâ€™m in a thousand places lately and forgetting things ğŸ™ŠğŸ™ˆ! note, you need cookie cutters :) if you make these, be sure to tag me so i can share ğŸ˜‰ off to spend the day with my boys!
.
for the cookie base:
3/4 cup coconut flour
3 tb arrowroot or tapioca flour
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup maple syrup
pinch salt
1/2 cup coconut oil, melted
.
for the cookie layer:
3/4 cup unsweetened shredded coconut + extra to sprinkle on top
1/2 cup coconut milk
3 tb honey
3 tb almond butter
*chocolate of choice to dip!
.
preheat oven to 325. line a baking sheet with parchment paper. in a medium bowl, mix together the ingredients for the cookie base, forming a ball. slightly roll and flatten onto the parchment paper. you need a 3 inch and a 1 inch cookie cutter. form 8 cookies using the cookie cutters. line them up on the baking sheet. bake 10-11 minutes until the cookies are just set and remove from oven. next, make the cookie layer. in a food processor, add coconut, coconut milk, honey and almond butter. the dough should be super thick and sticky. assemble the cookies â€” add about 2 tb of the cookie mixture on top of each cookie (I found it easiest to roll dough into small worms ğŸ› and press onto each cookie). melt chocolate in the microwave in 30 second increments. drizzle chocolate on top of each cookie. add more shredded coconut if youâ€™d like. place in fridge for 1-2 hours until set! #kalejunkie

STRAWBERRY CHOCOLATE CHIP MUG CAKE (mug cakes always inspired by my mama friend @sammyjaneeason)

tested. retested. and tested again, here is the recipe for my new PALEO LEMON POPPYSEED MUFFINS ğŸ‹ eeeeeeeeek they are so good, and i think some of my taste tester friends would agree (tell us, what did you think @biohackertodd? ğŸ˜‰) note, i havenâ€™t tested all the substitutions, so if your diet allows, iâ€™d suggest just making them as is! ğŸ‹
-
hereâ€™s what you need for the muffins:
2 1/4 cups almond flour
1/2 cup arrowroot flour
3 eggs
1/2 cup lemon juice (this is 4-5 lemons)
zest of two lemons
1/2 cup maple syrup
1/4 cup coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp baking soda
3 tb poppyseeds
1/4 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp salt
-
hereâ€™s how to make them:
preheat oven to 350. line a muffin tin with 12 liners. in a medium bowl, whisk together the eggs, lemon juice, lemon zest, maple syrup, coconut oil, and vanilla extract. you can also use a hand mixer to do this, but itâ€™s not necessary. in another medium bowl, mix together the almond flour, arrowroot flour, baking soda, poppyseeds, cinnamon, and salt. pour dry batter into the wet, mixing together, but being careful not to overmix. use a spoon to fill each muffin tin cup almost to the top. bake for 17-18 minutesâ€”the top will start to brown and a toothpick will come out clean.
-
for the drizzle, youâ€™ve got options:
if you like your muffins a little sweeter, whisk together 1 cup of powdered sugar and 3 tb water, until desired consistency is reached, and drizzle over each muffin.
you could also whisk together 1/2 coconut butter with 1/4 cup maple syrup, thinning with a little water as needed.
-
ENJOYYYYYY!!!!! #kalejunkie

i never really considered myself a MORNING GLORY MUFFIN kind of gal, but wouldnâ€™t you know, here i am ğŸ‘µğŸ¼ i made a version of my girl @lauraleabalancedâ€™s jumbo morning glory muffins, and yeah...pretty convinced that youâ€™re going to be obsessed too ğŸ’¯ you can find the original (banana-less) recipe on lauraâ€™s blog, and my version is here for you below! you can see what they look like inside on my IG stories. -
ingredients:
1 cup rolled oats
1 cup gluten free flour (or whole wheat or spelt)
1 banana
2 eggs
2 tsp baking soda
1 apple (i like pink lady)
2 medium carrots
1/2 cup raisins
2 tsp cinnamon
1/4 tsp nutmeg
3/4 cup full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup coconut sugar
2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup walnuts, chopped
pinch sea salt
-
instructions:
preheat oven to 350 and line a muffin tin with liners. in a medium bowl, mix together 1/2 cup of the oats, baking soda, flour, sea salt, coconut sugar, cinnamon, and nutmeg. set aside. in a food processor or blender, add remaining oats and pulse/blend until a flour consistency is formed, set aside. in another bowl, whisk together the eggs, vanilla, and coconut milk. next, core the apple, peel carrots, and add them to the blender, along with the banana. pulse/blend lightly until a crumble like consistency is formed. pour wet ingredients into dry, and fold in the raisins and walnuts, be sure not to overmix! spoon batter into each muffin cavity. i made regular size muffins and 28 min in the oven was perfect!
HAPPY SATURDAY! #kalejunkie
